On behalf of Chief of Police Todd Schmaderer, I am responding to your request for Omaha Police Department records. Your request is made pursuant to the provisions of the Nebraska Public Records Act. In your request dated May 25, 2025 you sought records related to ZN86097 to include the following: 

"The incident report and any supplements, such as Forensic photography taken in relation to shooting incident and captured CCTV security footage taken on the day of the incident at the Westroads Mall located in Omaha, Nebraska on the date of 12/05/07" 

This is the response required by NEB. REV. STAT. § 84-712, et seq. 
The Nebraska public records statute allows persons the right to examine public records in the possession of public agencies during normal agency business hours, to make memorandum and abstracts from those public records, and to obtain copies of public records in certain circumstances. The statute does not require a public agency to review documents and create abstracts or other lists, to answer questions, or to create documents that do not otherwise exist. See NEB.REV.STAT. § 84-712. Although the Nebraska public records statutes provided for access to public documents, such access is not absolute. The statutes also provide for exceptions to disclosures by express and special provisions; there are 21 categories of documents that may be kept confidential from the public at the discretion of the agency involved. See Neb. Rev. Stat. § 84-712.05. 

As defined in Neb. Rev Stat 84-712.05(5), supplemental reports, photographs, and security footage are considered records developed by law enforcement agencies charged with duties of investigation, and as such is not considered public record. Therefore, your request for these items is denied. 
Please visit the following link https://police.cityofomaha.org/request-a-police-report to request the public reports or call 402-444-5818. There is a $5 fee for each public report number. Reference ZN86097.

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Seattle Digital Kiosks: Mayor comms with DSA, IKE, city depts
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Since January 1. 2024:
1. All communications (including emails, attachments, text messages, calendar entries, memoranda, or summaries of verbal communications) sent or received by Mayor Bruce Harrell, Tim Burgess, or any staff member in the Mayor's Office acting on their behalf, regarding the proposed interactive digital kiosks (IKE Smart City/Downtown Seattle Association). This includes, but is not limited to, communications with:
- The Seattle City Council (any Councilmembers or their staff)
- The Seattle Department of Transportation (SDOT)
- The Seattle Information Technology Department (Seattle IT)
- The Seattle Design Commission
- The Seattle Disability Commission
- Representatives of the Downtown Seattle Association (DSA)
- Representatives of IKE Smart City / Orange Barrel Media
2. Any internal memoranda, briefing documents, meeting agendas, or meeting minutes within the Office of the Mayor related to the digital kiosk proposal, its review by city bodies, its surveillance or privacy implications, or strategies for its approval and implementation.
3. Records of any meetings (including attendee lists, agendas, minutes, and materials presented) where Mayor Bruce Harrell, Tim Burgess, or other staff from the Mayor's Office discussed the digital kiosk project with representatives of the Downtown Seattle Association, IKE Smart City, or other business interests.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Phil Mocek
